  "prompt": "What is the heaviest weight ever lifted by a human being?",
  "response": "The title of the \"heaviest weight ever lifted by a human being\" can vary depending on the type of lift and the context in which it was performed. Here are some of the most significant records and feats in different lifting disciplines:\n\n### **1. Deadlift**\n- **Hafthor Bj\u00f6rnsson**: In May 2020, the Icelandic strongman completed a **501 kg (1,104 lb)** deadlift. This lift surpassed the previous record of **500 kg (1,102 lb)** set by **Eddie Hall** in July 2016. Both lifts were performed under strongman competition conditions, which may differ slightly from standardized powerlifting competitions.\n\n### **2. Backlift**\n- **Paul Anderson**: Often celebrated as one of the strongest men ever, Anderson reportedly performed a **backlift of 6,270 lbs (2,840 kg)** in 1957. In this feat, he lifted a platform loaded with heavy weights using his back. However, it's important to note that this lift was not performed under official competition standards and thus isn't officially recognized by modern sporting bodies.\n\n### **3. Olympic Weightlifting**\n- **Lasha Talakhadze**: In the realm of Olympic weightlifting, which includes the snatch and clean & jerk lifts, **Lasha Talakhadze** of Georgia set a world record by lifting **267 kg (588 lb)** in the clean and jerk at the 2021 World Championships. This lift is recognized by the International Weightlifting Federation (IWF).\n\n### **4. Powerlifting Total**\n- **Ray Williams**: Competing in the super heavyweight category, **Ray Williams** has achieved a total combined lift (squat, bench press, and deadlift) exceeding **1,100 kg (2,425 lb)** in sanctioned powerlifting meets. These totals are the sum of maximum lifts across the three disciplines and are subject to strict competition rules.\n\n### **5. Historical Feats**\n- **Various Strongmen**: Throughout history, numerous strongmen have claimed extraordinary lifts that exceed modern records. While impressive, many of these claims lack official verification and are often considered part of strongman folklore.\n\n### **Summary**\n- **Heaviest Deadlift**: Hafthor Bj\u00f6rnsson with **501 kg (1,104 lb)**\n- **Heaviest Backlift**: Paul Anderson with **6,270 lb (2,840 kg)** (unofficial)\n- **Heaviest Clean & Jerk**: Lasha Talakhadze with **267 kg (588 lb)**\n- **Highest Powerlifting Total**: Over **1,100 kg (2,425 lb)** by elite powerlifters\n\nEach of these records highlights the incredible strength and dedication of athletes in their respective disciplines. It's also worth noting that lifting techniques, equipment, and regulations can vary, making direct comparisons between different types of lifts and records challenging.",
